{"title_page": "Aosta Valley", "text_new": "{{redirect|Valle d'Aosta|the wine region|Valle d'Aosta DOC}}\n{{inconsistent citations}}\n{{short description|Autonomous region of Italy}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n<!-- See Template:Infobox settlement for additional fields and descriptions -->\n| name                    = Aosta Valley\n| native_name           = {{native name|it|Valle d'Aosta}}<br />{{native name|fr|Vall\u00e9e d'Aoste}} \n| native_name_lang        = \n| settlement_type         = [[Autonomous regions with special statute|Autonomous region of Italy]]\n| short_description       = Autonomous region of Italy\n| image_skyline           = \n| image_alt               = \n| image_caption           = \n| image_flag              = Flag of Valle d'Aosta.svg\n| flag_alt                = \n| image_shield            = Valle d'Aosta-Stemma.svg\n| shield_size             = 50px\n| shield_alt              = \n| image_blank_emblem      = \n| blank_emblem_size       = \n| blank_emblem_type       = \n| blank_emblem_alt        = \n| nickname                = \n| motto                   = \n| anthem                  = ''[[Montagnes Vald\u00f4taines]]''\n| image_map               = Aosta Valley in Italy.svg\n| mapsize                 = \n| map_alt                 = \n| map_caption             = \n| pushpin_map             = \n| pushpin_label_position  = \n| pushpin_map_alt         = \n| pushpin_mapsize         = \n| pushpin_map_caption     = \n| coordinates             = {{coord|45 |44 |49|N|7 |26 |21|E|display=inline,title}}\n| coor_pinpoint           = \n| coordinates_footnotes   = \n| subdivision_type        = Country\n| subdivision_name        = [[Italy]]\n| established_title       = \n| established_date        = \n| founder                 = \n| named_for               = \n| seat_type               = Capital\n| seat                    = [[Aosta]]\n| government_footnotes    = \n| government_type         = \n| leader_party            = [[For Our Valley|PNV]]\n| leader_title            = President\n| leader_name             = [[Antonio Fosson]]\n| leader_title1           = \n| leader_name1            = \n| total_type              = \n| unit_pref               = \n| area_magnitude          = \n| area_footnotes          =\n| area_total_km2          = 3263\n| elevation_footnotes     = \n| elevation_max_m         = \n| elevation_min_m         = \n| population_footnotes    = \n| population_total        = 126933\n| population_as_of        = 30-10-2012\n| population_density_km2  = auto\n| population_demonym      = {{lang-en|Aostan}} or Valdostan<br>{{lang-it|Valdostano}} (man)<br>{{lang-it|Valdostana}} (woman)<br>{{lang-fr|Vald\u00f4tain}} (man)<br>{{lang-fr|Vald\u00f4taine}} (woman)\n| population_note         = \n| population_blank1_title = Official languages<ref name=statut>{{cite web |title=Statut sp\u00e9cial de la Vallee d'Aoste|volume=Titre VI Art. 38 |year=2001 |publisher=Conseil r\u00e9gional de la Vall\u00e9e d'Aoste |language=fr |url=http://www.consiglio.regione.vda.it/statuto/statuto_f.asp |accessdate=2015-10-25 }}</ref>\n| population_blank1       = [[Italian language|Italian]], [[French language|French]]\n| demographics_type1      = Citizenship\n| demographics1_footnotes = <ref name=StatDemo>{{cite web|url=http://demo.istat.it/str2007/query.php?lingua=ita&Rip=S1&Reg=R02&Pro=P000&Com=&paese=A9999&submit=Tavola |title=Statistiche demografiche ISTAT |publisher=Demo.istat.it |date= |accessdate=2010-04-22|language=it}}</ref>\n| demographics1_title1    = Italian\n| demographics1_info1     = 95%\n| demographics1_title2    = \n| demographics1_info2     = \n| demographics1_title3    = \n| demographics1_info3     = \n| timezone1               = [[Central European Time|CET]]\n| utc_offset1             = +1\n| timezone1_DST           = [[Central European Summer Time|CEST]]\n| utc_offset1_DST         = +2\n| postal_code_type        = \n| postal_code             = \n| area_code_type          = [[ISO 3166 code]] \n| area_code               = IT-23 \n| blank_name_sec1         = [[List of Italian regions by GDP|GDP (nominal)]]\n| blank_info_sec1         = \u20ac4.4 billion (2017)<ref name=GDP>{{cite press release |url=https://ec.europa.eu/eurostat/documents/2995521/9618249/1-26022019-AP-EN.pdf/f765d183-c3d2-4e2f-9256-cc6665909c80 |title=Regional GDP per capita ranged from 31% to 626% of the EU average in 2017 |publisher=ec.europa.eu |accessdate=2 September 2019}}</ref>\n| blank1_name_sec1        = [[List of Italian regions by GDP|GDP per capita]]\n| blank1_info_sec1        = \u20ac35,200 (2017)<ref name=GDP/>\n| blank2_name_sec1         = [[Human Development Index|HDI]] (2017)\n| blank2_info_sec1         = 0.875<ref name=\"GlobalDataLab\">{{Cite web|url=https://hdi.globaldatalab.org/areadata/shdi/|title=Sub-national HDI - Area Database - Global Data Lab|website=hdi.globaldatalab.org|language=en|access-date=2018-09-13}}</ref><br/>{{color|green|very high}} \u00b7 [[List of Italian regions by Human Development Index|14th of 21]]\n| blank_name_sec2         = [[First-level NUTS of the European Union#Italy|NUTS Region]]\n| blank_info_sec2         = ITC\n| website                 = [http://www.regione.vda.it www.regione.vda.it]\n| footnotes               = \n}}\n\nThe '''Aosta Valley''' ({{lang-it|Valle d'Aosta}} {{IPA-it|\u02c8valle da\u02c8\u0254sta|}} (official) or {{lang|it|Val d'Aosta}} (usual); {{lang-fr|Vall\u00e9e d'Aoste}} {{IPA-fr|vale d\u0254st|}}<ref>[[Aostan French]] pronunciation - Jean-Marie Pierret, ''Phon\u00e9tique historique du fran\u00e7ais et notions de phon\u00e9tique g\u00e9n\u00e9rale'', Peeters, Louvain-la-Neuve, 1994, p.|104.</ref> (official) or {{lang|fr|Val d'Aoste}} (usual); {{lang-frp|Val d'Outa}} (usual); {{lang-wae|Augschtalann}} or {{lang|wae|Ougstalland}}; {{lang-pms|Val d'Osta}}) is a mountainous [[autonomous regions with special statute|autonomous]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.regione.vda.it/autonomia_istituzioni/lostatuto_f.aspx |title=Le Statut sp\u00e9cial de la Vall\u00e9e d'Aoste |date=1948 |accessdate=2017-07-10}} Articles 1 and 48b of the constitutional law officially assert the region's autonomy.</ref> [[Regions of Italy|region]] in northwestern [[Italy]]. It is bordered by [[Auvergne-Rh\u00f4ne-Alpes]], [[France]], to the west, [[Valais]], [[Switzerland]], to the north and by [[Piedmont]], [[Italy]], to the south and east. The regional [[Capital city|capital]] is [[Aosta]].\n\nCovering an area of {{convert|3263|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}} and with a population of about 128,000 it is the smallest, least populous, and least densely populated region of Italy. It is the only [[Italian regions|Italian region]] that is not sub-divided into provinces (the province of Aosta was dissolved in 1945).<ref name=\"camera.it\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.camera.it/_dati/leg13/lavori/bollet/200007/0718/pdf/06.pdf|title=Italian Parliament - VI Commission document 2000-07-18 (in Italian)}}</ref> Provincial administrative functions are provided by the regional government. The region is divided into 74 ''[[Comuni of the Aosta Valley|comuni]]'' ({{lang-fr|communes}}).\n\n[[Italian language|Italian]] and [[French language|French]] are the official languages,<ref name=statut/> though the native population also speak [[Vald\u00f4tain dialect|Vald\u00f4tain]], a dialect of [[Franco-Proven\u00e7al language|Arpitan (Franco-Proven\u00e7al)]]; 50.53% of the population can speak all three languages.<ref name=\"Vall\u00e9e d 2009, p. 20\">{{cite book |editor-last1=Decime |editor-first1=R. |editor-last2=Vernetto |editor-first2=G. |year=2009 |title=Profil de la politique linguistique de la Vall\u00e9e d'Aoste |publisher=Le Ch\u00e2teau |p=20 |language=fr }}</ref>\n\n==Geography==\n[[File:Champillon, Valpelline Valley (38437829771).jpg|thumb|left|200px|A view from refuge Champillon, [[Valpelline (valley)|Valpelline]]]]\nThe Aosta Valley is an Alpine valley which with its tributary valleys includes the Italian slopes of [[Mont Blanc]], [[Monte Rosa]], [[Gran Paradiso]] and the [[Matterhorn]]; its highest peak is [[Mont Blanc]] ({{cvt|4810|m|ft|disp=or}}). This makes it the highest region in Italy by [[list of Italian regions by highest point]].\n\n===Climate===\n\nThe valleys, usually above {{convert|1,600|m}}, annually have a Cold [[Continental climate|Continental Climate]] (''Dfc''). In this climate the snow season is very long, as long as 8 or 9 months at the highest points. During the summer, [[mist]] occurs almost every day. These areas are the wettest in the western Alps. Temperatures are low, between {{convert|-7|\u00b0C|0|abbr=on}} and {{convert|-3|\u00b0C|0|abbr=on}} in January, and in July between {{convert|20|\u00b0C|0|abbr=on}} and {{convert|35|\u00b0C|0|abbr=on}}. In this area is the town of [[Rh\u00eames-Notre-Dame]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Guida alla consultazione del bollettino meteorologico della Regione Autonoma Valle d'Aosta con elementi di meteorologia alpina |url=http://cf.regione.vda.it/download.php?fileID=74&lang=ita |publisher=Valle d'Aosta Official Website |language=it }}</ref> which may be the coldest town in the Western Alps and where the winter average temperature is around {{convert|-7|\u00b0C|0|abbr=on}}.{{citation needed|date=May 2016}}\n\nAreas between {{convert|2,000|and|3,500|m}} usually have a [[Tundra]] Climate ([[K\u00f6ppen climate classification#GROUP E: Polar climates|ET]]), where every month has an average temperature below {{convert|10|\u00b0C|0|abbr=on}}. This climate may be a kind of more severe Cold Oceanic Climate, with a low summer average but mild winters, sometimes above {{convert|-3|\u00b0C|0|abbr=on}}, especially near lakes, or a more severe Cold Continental Climate, with a very low winter average. Temperature averages in [[Plateau Rosa]], at {{convert|3400|m}} high, are {{convert|-11.6|\u00b0C|abbr=on}} in January and {{convert|1.4|\u00b0C|abbr=on}} in July. It is the coldest place in Italy where the climate is verifiable.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.meteoam.it/ta/infoStazione/LIMH | title=Tempo in atto su Plateau Rosa | publisher=meteoam.it | work=meteoam.it | accessdate=2020-01-21 | year=2012}}</ref>\n\nIn the past, above {{convert|3,500|m}}, all months had an average temperature below freezing, with a Perpetual Frost Climate (EF). In recent years though there was a rise in temperatures. See as an example the data for Plateau Rosa.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.meteoam.it/ta/infoStazione/LIMH | title=Tempo in atto su Plateau Rosa | publisher=meteoam.it | work=meteoam.it | accessdate=2020-01-21 | year=2012}}</ref>\n\n<gallery mode=\"packed\" heights=\"140\" style=\"font-size:88%;line-height:120%\">\nFile:Mont Blanc, Mont Maudit, Mont Blanc du Tacul.jpg|[[Mont Blanc]]\nFile:Cervino dal Lac Bleu.jpg|Lago Blu and the [[Matterhorn]]\nFile:Castor - Monte Castore.jpg|[[Castor (mountain)|Mount Castor]]\n</gallery>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Aosta.jpg|thumb|left|upright=1.1|View of [[Aosta]]]]\nThe first inhabitants of the Aosta Valley were [[Celts]] and [[Ligures]], whose [[Ligurian language (ancient)|language]] heritage remains in some local placenames. Rome conquered the region from the local [[Salassi]] around 25 BC and founded ''Augusta Pr\u00e6toria Salassorum'' (modern-day Aosta) to secure the strategic mountain passes, and they went on to build bridges and roads through the mountains. Thus, the name ''Valle d'Aosta'' literally means \"Valley of Augustus\".<ref>{{cite news | archive-date=July 19, 2012 | archive-url=https://archive.is/20120719045637/http://valdostadailytimes.com/features/x546438866/What-does-Valdosta-mean | title=What does Valdosta mean? | date=October 12, 2009 | last=Poling | first=Dean | periodical=Valdosta Daily Times | url=http://valdostadailytimes.com/features/x546438866/What-does-Valdosta-mean | accessdate=2013-02-21 | url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n[[File:The Astronomical Observatory of the Aosta Valley.jpg|thumb|right|The Astronomical Observatory of the Aosta Valley, in Saint-Barth\u00e9lemy ([[Nus]]).<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.eso.org/public/announcements/ann13044/ | title=ESO Astronomy Camp for Secondary School Students | work=eso.org | date=13 May 2013 | accessdate=15 May 2013}}</ref>]]\n\nIn 1031\u20131032, [[Humbert I of Savoy]], the founder of the [[House of Savoy]], received the title ''Count of Aosta'' from Emperor [[Conrad II, Holy Roman Emperor|Conrad II]] of the [[Franconia]]n line and built himself a [[Fort Bard|commanding fortification at Bard]]. Saint [[Anselm of Canterbury]] was born in Aosta in 1033 or 1034. The region was divided among strongly fortified [[castle]]s, and in 1191, [[Thomas I of Savoy]] found it necessary to grant to the communes a ''Charte des franchises'' (\"Charter of Liberties\") which preserved autonomy\u2014rights that were fiercely defended until 1770, when they were revoked in order to tie Aosta more closely to [[Piedmont]], but which were again demanded during post-Napoleonic times. In the mid-13th century, [[Frederick II, Holy Roman Emperor|Emperor Frederick II]] made the County of Aosta a [[duchy]] (see [[Duke of Aosta]]), and its arms charged with a lion rampant were carried in the [[Savoy]] arms until the reunification of Italy in 1870.<ref>{{cite web |author=Fran\u00e7ois Velde |year=2000 |title=Heraldry in the House of Savoia |url=http://www.heraldica.org/topics/national/italy1.htm |publisher=Heraldica |accessdate=2010-04-22}}</ref>\n\nThe region remained part of Savoy lands, with the exceptions of French occupations from 1539 to 1563, later in 1691, then between 1704 and 1706. It was also ruled by the [[First French Empire]] between 1800 and 1814. During French rule, it was part of Aoste [[arrondissement]] in [[Doire (department)|Doire]] department.<ref name=Gallica>[http://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k204214z/f388.image Almanach Imp\u00e9rial an bissextil MDCCCXII], pp. 392\u2013393, accessed in [[Gallica]] 18 February 2015 {{in lang|fr}}</ref> As part of the [[Kingdom of Sardinia]], it joined the new [[Kingdom of Italy]] in 1861.\n\nFrench forces briefly controlled the area at the end of [[World War II]], but withdrew under [[United Kingdom|British]] and [[United States|American]] pressure.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Harris |first1=Charles Reginald Schiller |title=Allied military administration of Italy, 1943-1945 |date=1957 |publisher=H. M. Stationery Office |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=Xks1AAAAIAAJ&q=|pages=318\u201320}}</ref> The region gained [[Autonomous regions with special statute (Italy)|special autonomous status]] after the end of World War II; the province of Aosta ceased to exist in 1945.<ref name=\"camera.it\"/>\n\n==Government and politics==\n{{Main|Politics of Aosta Valley}}\nFor more than 20 years the valley has been dominated by autonomist regional parties. The last [[Valdostan regional election, 2018|regional election]] was held in May 2018. On 27 June 2018 Nicoletta Spelgatti of the [[Lega Nord]] was elected president by the region's cabinet. She is the first woman and the first Lega Nord member to hold the position.<ref name=\"reg-it June2018\">{{cite news |title=Valle d'Aosta: Nicoletta Spelgatti (Lega) nuovo presidente Regione |url=http://www.regioni.it/riforme/2018/06/27/valle-daosta-nicoletta-spelgatti-lega-nuovo-presidente-regione-567702/ |work=Regioni.it |date=27 June 2018 |language=it}}</ref>\n\n==Demographics==\n\n{{multiple image\n| align = left\n| image1 = Bruil, Rhemes Valley (38406553102).jpg\n| width1 = 190\n| alt1 = \n| image2 = Casa Valdostana Cretaz Valtournenche.JPG\n| width2 = 200\n| footer = Typical Alpine houses in [[Rh\u00eames-Notre-Dame]] (left) and [[Valtournenche]] (right)\n}}\n{{Historical populations\n|type =\n|footnote = Source: [[Istituto Nazionale di Statistica|ISTAT]] 2001\n|1861 |81884\n|1871 |81260\n|1881 |85007\n|1901 |83529\n|1911 |80680\n|1921 |82769\n|1931 |83479\n|1936 |83455\n|1951 |94140\n|1961 |100959\n|1971 |109150\n|1981 |112353\n|1991 |115938\n|2001 |119548\n|2011 |128000\n|2017 |126883\n}}\n\nThe population density of Aosta Valley is by far the lowest of the Italian regions. In 2008, 38.9 inhabitants per km<sup>2</sup> were registered in the region, whereas the average national figure was 198.8, though the region has extensive uninhabitable areas of mountain and glacier, with a substantial part of the population living in the central valley. Migration from tributary valleys has now been stemmed by generous regional support for agriculture and tourist development. {{citation needed|date=October 2014}}\n\nThe population is growing slowly but steadily. Negative [[population growth]] since 1976 has been more than offset by immigration. The region has one of Italy's lowest [[birth rate]]s, with a rising average age. This, too, is partly compensated by immigration, since most immigrants arriving in the region are younger people working in the tourist industry. Between 1991 and 2001, the population of Aosta Valley grew by 3.1%, which is the highest growth among the Italian regions. With a negative natural population growth, this is due exclusively to positive net migration.<ref name=StatDemo/> Between 2001 and 2011, the population of Aosta Valley grew by a further 7.07%. {{As of|2006}}, the Italian [[National Institute of Statistics (Italy)|National Institute of Statistics]] (ISTAT) estimated that 4,976 foreign-born immigrants live in Aosta Valley, equal to 4.0% of the total regional population.\n\nThe [[Vald\u00f4tain]] population and their language dialects have been the subject of some sociological research.<ref>{{Cite journal |first=Chantal |last=Saint-Blancat |year=1984 |title=The Effect of Minority Group Vitality upon Its Sociopsychological Behaviour and Strategies |journal=Journal of Multilingual and Multicultural Development |volume=5 |issue=6 |pages=511\u2013516 |url=http://www.eric.ed.gov/ERICWebPortal/search/detailmini.jsp?_nfpb=true&_&ERICExtSearch_SearchValue_0=EJ313919&ERICExtSearch_SearchType_0=no&accno=EJ313919 |doi=10.1080/01434632.1984.9994177}}<br>{{Cite journal |last=Cooper |first=Danielle Chavy |year=1987 |title=Voices from the Alps: Literature in Val d'Aoste Today |journal=World Literature Today |volume=61 |issue=1 |pages=24\u201327 |jstor=40142443 |doi=10.2307/40142443 }}</ref>\n\n==Culture==\n===Languages===\n{{main|Aostan French|Vald\u00f4tain dialect}}\nThe Aosta Valley was the first government authority to adopt Modern French as the official language in 1536, three years before [[France]] itself.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Caniggia |first1=Mauro |last2=Poggianti |first2=Luca |date=2012-10-25 |title=La Vall\u00e9e d'Aoste: enclave francophone au sud-est du Mont Blanc |url=http://zigzag-francophonie.eu/ITALIE-Le-Val-d-Aoste |publisher=Zigzag magazine |language=fr |accessdate=2013-11-28 }}</ref> Italian and French are nowadays the region's [[official language]]s,<ref name=statut/> and are used for the regional government's acts and laws, though Italian is much more widely spoken in everyday life, and French is mostly spoken in cultural life. Education is conducted evenly in French and Italian,<ref name=statut/> so that anyone who has gone to school in the Aosta Valley can speak French to at least a medium-high level.<ref name=aostebi>{{cite web |author=AA. VV. |title=Une Vall\u00e9e d'Aoste bilingue dans une Europe plurilingue |others=in French and Italian |url=http://www.fondchanoux.org/scarica.aspx?id=29 |location=Aoste |publisher=Fondation Emile Chanoux |accessdate=2015-04-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924014323/http://www.fondchanoux.org/scarica.aspx?id=29 |archive-date=2015-09-24 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe [[regional language]], known as ''patou\u00e9 valdot\u00e8n'' or simply ''patou\u00e9'' (''valdostano'' in Italian, ''vald\u00f4tain'' in French), is a [[dialect|dialectal variety]] of [[Franco-Proven\u00e7al language|Franco-Proven\u00e7al]]. It is spoken as a [[native language|native]] and [[second language]] by 68,000 residents, or about 58% of the population according to a sociolinguistic survey carried out by the ''Fondation \u00c9mile Chanoux'' in 2001.<ref name=2001survey>{{Cite web|url=http://www.fondchanoux.org/sondaggiolinguisticod.aspx|title=Sondaggio linguistico: Q 0301 Lingua materna - Qual \u00e8 la sua lingua materna?|website=Fondation \u00c9mile Chanoux|language=it}}</ref>\n\nThe survey found out that the Italian language was spoken as a mother tongue by 77.29% of respondents, Franco-Proven\u00e7al by 17.91%, while French by 1.25%. The residents of the villages of [[Gressoney-Saint-Jean]], [[Gressoney-La-Trinit\u00e9]] and [[Issime]], in the [[Lys Valley]], speak two dialects of [[Walser German]], [[Titsch]] and [[T\u00f6itschu]], respectively.<ref name=\"aostebi\" /> According to the survey, [[Walser German]] was spoken as a mother tongue by 207 people, or 17.78%, in these three villages. Nevertheless, it was known to 56.38% of the population.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.fondchanoux.org/sondaggiolingusticowd.aspx|title=Sondaggio Linguistico Comunit\u00e0 Walser|website=Fondation \u00c9mile Chanoux|language=it}}</ref>\n\n{{bar box\n|title = Mother tongues in the Aosta Valley (2001)<ref name=2001survey/>\n|titlebar=#ddd |left1=  |right1= |float=left |width=350px\n|bars =\n{{bar percent|[[Italian language|Italian]]|green|77.29}}\n{{bar percent|[[Vald\u00f4tain]] ([[Franco-Proven\u00e7al]])|blue|17.91}}\n{{bar percent|[[Aostan French]]|red|1.25}}\n{{bar percent|Other languages|yellow|4.95}}\n}}{{bar box\n|title = Use of languages by the population (2001)<ref name=2001survey/>\n|titlebar=#ddd |left1=  |right1= |float=left |width=350px\n|bars =\n{{bar percent|[[Italian language|Italian]]|green|96.01}}\n{{bar percent|[[Aostan French]]|red|75.41}}\n{{bar percent|[[Vald\u00f4tain]] ([[Franco-Proven\u00e7al]])|blue|55.77}}\n{{bar percent|All three languages|yellow|50.53}}\n}}\n{{clear}}\n\n===Castles===\n[[File:Villeneuve Chatel Argent 02.jpg|thumb|right|[[Ch\u00e2tel-Argent]]]]\n[[File:11CastelloDiSaintPierre.jpg|thumb|The [[Saint-Pierre Castle]].<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20151228110543/http://museoscienze.it/?lang=en Aosta Valley Regional Museum of Natural Science] museoscienze.it</ref>]]\n[[File:Fenis Castle1.JPG|thumb|The [[F\u00e9nis Castle]], 13th century]]\nThere are a numerous medieval castles and fortified houses in the Aosta Valley, including [[Ch\u00e2tel-Argent]], [[Saint-Pierre Castle]], [[F\u00e9nis Castle]], [[Issogne Castle]], [[Ussel Castle]], [[Sarre Castle]], [[Cly Castle]], and [[Ch\u00e2telard Castle, Aosta Valley|Ch\u00e2telard Castle]].<ref name=mass>Massetti, E. [http://www.naturaosta.it/castles.htm \"Aosta Valley Castles\"] n.d., accessed 15 March 2014.</ref> [[Savoy Castle (Gressoney-Saint-Jean)|Savoy Castle]] in [[Gressoney-Saint-Jean]] was conceived in the 19th century and completed in 1904.<ref name=mass/> Since 1990, it has also been home to the [[Savoy Castle Alpine Botanical Garden]].\n\n===Cuisine===\nThe cuisine of Aosta Valley is characterized by simplicity and revolves around \"robust\" ingredients such as [[potato]]es, [[polenta]]; [[cheese]] and [[meat]]; and [[rye bread]]. Many of the dishes involve [[Fontina]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Fontina |url=http://www.lovevda.it/en/food-and-wine/products/cheese/fontina |publisher=Valle D'Aosta Official Tourism Website |year=2014 |accessdate=2015-10-23}}</ref> a cheese with [[Protected Geographical Status|PDO]] status, made from cow's milk that originates from the valley. It is found in dishes such as the soup ''\u00e0 la v\u00e2peuleun\u00e8ntse''<ref>{{cite web |title=Seupa \u00e0 la Vapelenentse (Valpelline Soup) |url=http://www.lovevda.it/en/food-and-wine/recipes/vapelenentse-soup |publisher=Valle D'Aosta Official Tourism Website |year=2014 |accessdate=2015-10-23}}</ref> ([[Valpelline, Aosta Valley|Valpelline]] Soup). Other cheeses made in the region are [[Toma cheese|Tomme de Gressoney]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Gressoney toma cheese |url=http://www.lovevda.it/en/food-and-wine/products/cheese/gressoney-toma|publisher=Aosta Valley Official Tourism Website |year=2014 |accessdate=2015-10-23}}</ref> and Seras. [[Valle d'Aosta Fromadzo|Fromadzo]] ([[Vald\u00f4tain]] for ''cheese'') has been produced locally since the 15th century and also has PDO status.<ref>{{cite web |title=Fromadzo cheese |url=http://www.lovevda.it/en/food-and-wine/products/cheese/fromadzo |publisher=Valle D'Aosta Official Tourism Website |year=2014 |accessdate=2015-10-23}}</ref>\n\nRegional specialities, besides Fontina, are ''Motzetta'' (dried [[chamois]] meat, prepared like [[prosciutto]]), [[Vall\u00e9e d'Aoste Lard d'Arnad]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Valle\u00e9 d'Aoste Lard d'Arnad |url=http://www.lovevda.it/en/food-and-wine/products/charcuterie/vallee-d-aoste-lard-d-arnad |publisher=Aosta Valley Official Tourism Website |year=2014 |accessdate=2015-10-23}}</ref> (a cured and brined [[fatback]] product with PDO designation), [[Vall\u00e9e d'Aoste Jambon de Bosses]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Vall\u00e9e d'Aoste Jambon de Bosses |url=http://www.lovevda.it/en/food-and-wine/products/charcuterie/vallee-d-aoste-jambon-de-bosses |publisher=Aosta Valley Official Tourism Website |year=2014 |accessdate=2015-10-23}}</ref> (a kind of [[ham]], likewise with PDO designation), and a black bread.\n\nNotable dishes include ''Carbonnade'', consisting of salt-cured beef cooked with onions and red wine served with [[polenta]]; breaded [[veal]] cutlets called ''costolette''; ''teuteuns'',<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.lovevda.it/en/food-and-wine/products/charcuterie/teuteun |title=The Teuteun |publisher=Valle D'Aosta Official Tourism Website |year=2014 |accessdate=2015-10-23 }}</ref> salt-cured cow's [[udder]] that is cooked and sliced; and ''steak \u00e0 la vald\u00f4taine'',<ref>{{cite web |title=Steak Valdaostan style |url=http://www.fontina-dop.it/ricetta_3_gb.html |publisher=Consorzio Produttori e Tutela Della Fontina DOP |language=it |accessdate=2015-10-23 }}</ref> a steak with [[cro\u00fbton]]s, ham and melted cheese.\n\n===Wine growing===\n{{See also|Valle d'Aosta DOC}}\nNotable wines include two white wines from [[Morgex]] (''Blanc de Morgex et de La Salle'' and ''Chaudelune''), a red wine blend from Arvier (''Enfer d'Arvier'') and one from [[Gamay]].<ref>{{cite web |title=D.O.C. Wine |url=http://www.lovevda.it/en/food-and-wine/wines |publisher=Valle D'Aosta Official Tourism Website |year=2014 |accessdate=2015-10-23 }}</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery mode=\"packed\" heights=\"130\" style=\"font-size:88%;line-height:120%\">\nFile:Sito archeologico di Chenal 1120484.JPG|The prehistoric site near Chenal castle, [[Montjovet]], rich in [[petroglyph]]\nFile:La Thuile-Rifugio Deffeyes 2.jpg|A view from refuge Albert Deffeyes, [[La Thuile, Italy|La Thuile]]\nFile:Capra ibex gran paradiso.jpg|Male [[Alpine Ibex]] in [[Gran Paradiso National Park]]\nFile:Marmotta alpina (Marmota marmota).jpg| [[Alpine marmot]] in [[Gran Paradiso National Park]]\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Italy|European Union}}\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[Alps-Mediterranean Euroregion]]\n* [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Aosta]]\n* [[Elections in Aosta Valley]]\n* [[Mont Blanc]]\n* [[List of Presidents of Aosta Valley]]\n* [[Arch of Augustus (Aosta)|Arch of Augustus in Aosta]]\n* [[Roman Theatre, Aosta]]\n* [[Pont d'A\u00ebl|Roman bridge Pont d'A\u00ebl]]\n* [[Bridge of Grand Arvou|13th-century bridge of Grand Arvou]]\n* [[Fort Bard|Fort Bard\u2014Museum of the Alps]]\n* [[Mont Blanc Tunnel]]\n* [[Gran Paradiso National Park]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Sources==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{Cite journal | last=Cerutti | first=Augusta Vittoria | title=Le Pays de la Doire et son peuple | publisher=\u00e9diteur Musumeci | location=[[Quart, Italy|Quart]] | year=| isbn=| page= }}\n* {{Cite journal | last=Colliard | first=Lin | title=La culture vald\u00f4taine au cours des si\u00e8cles | location=Aoste | year=1976 | isbn=| page= }}\n* {{Cite journal | last=Henry | first=Joseph-Marie | title=Histoire de la Vall\u00e9e d'Aoste | publisher=Imprimerie Marguerettaz | location=Aoste | year=1967 | isbn=| page= }}\n* {{Cite journal | last=Janin | first=Bernard | title=Le Val d'Aoste. Tradition et renouveau | publisher=\u00e9diteur Musumeci | location=[[Quart, Italy|Quart]] | year=1976 | isbn=| page= }}\n* {{Cite journal | last=Riccarand | first=Elio | title=Storia della Valle d'Aosta contemporanea (1919-1945) | publisher=Stylos Aoste | location=Aoste | year=| isbn=| page= }}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikivoyage|Aosta Valley}}\n{{Commons|Aosta Valley}}\n* [http://www.regione.vda.it/ Website of the Aosta Valley Regional Authority] (in Italian and French)\n** [http://www.regione.vda.it/imagevallee/default_i.asp Photo gallery of the Aosta Valley]\n** [http://cf.regione.vda.it/ Weather forecast and map of the Aosta Valley]\n* [http://www.mondimedievali.net/Castelli/valdaosta.htm Castes and fortresses] at mondimedievali.net {{in lang|it}}\n\n{{Aosta Valley|nocat=yes}}\n{{Comuni of Aosta Valley|nocat=yes}}\n{{Regions of Italy}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Aosta Valley| ]]\n[[Category:Autonomous regions of Italy]]\n[[Category:Arpitany]]\n[[Category:Provinces of Italy]]\n[[Category:Regions of Italy]]\n[[Category:Valleys of Italy]]\n[[Category:Valleys of the Alps]]\n[[Category:Castles in Aosta Valley]]\n[[Category:French-speaking countries and territories]]\n[[Category:NUTS 2 statistical regions of the European Union]]\n[[Category:Regions of Europe with multiple official languages]]\n[[Category:Wine regions of Italy]]\n", "text_old": "{{redirect|Valle d'Aosta|the wine region|Valle d'Aosta DOC}}\n{{inconsistent citations}}\n{{short description|Autonomous region of Italy}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n<!-- See Template:Infobox settlement for additional fields and descriptions -->\n| name                    = Aosta Valley\n| native_name           = {{native name|it|Valle d'Aosta}}<br />{{native name|fr|Vall\u00e9e d'Aoste}} \n| native_name_lang        = \n| settlement_type         = [[Autonomous regions with special statute|Autonomous region of Italy]]\n| short_description       = Autonomous region of Italy\n| image_skyline           = \n| image_alt               = \n| image_caption           = \n| image_flag              = Flag of Valle d'Aosta.svg\n| flag_alt                = \n| image_shield            = Valle d'Aosta-Stemma.svg\n| shield_size             = 50px\n| shield_alt              = \n| image_blank_emblem      = \n| blank_emblem_size       = \n| blank_emblem_type       = \n| blank_emblem_alt        = \n| nickname                = \n| motto                   = \n| anthem                  = ''[[Montagnes Vald\u00f4taines]]''\n| image_map               = Aosta Valley in Italy.svg\n| mapsize                 = \n| map_alt                 = \n| map_caption             = \n| pushpin_map             = \n| pushpin_label_position  = \n| pushpin_map_alt         = \n| pushpin_mapsize         = \n| pushpin_map_caption     = \n| coordinates             = {{coord|45 |44 |49|N|7 |26 |21|E|display=inline,title}}\n| coor_pinpoint           = \n| coordinates_footnotes   = \n| subdivision_type        = Country\n| subdivision_name        = [[Italy]]\n| established_title       = \n| established_date        = \n| founder                 = \n| named_for               = \n| seat_type               = Capital\n| seat                    = [[Aosta]]\n| government_footnotes    = \n| government_type         = \n| leader_party            = [[For Our Valley|PNV]]\n| leader_title            = President\n| leader_name             = Antonio Fosson\n| leader_title1           = \n| leader_name1            = \n| total_type              = \n| unit_pref               = \n| area_magnitude          = \n| area_footnotes          =\n| area_total_km2          = 3263\n| elevation_footnotes     = \n| elevation_max_m         = \n| elevation_min_m         = \n| population_footnotes    = \n| population_total        = 126933\n| population_as_of        = 30-10-2012\n| population_density_km2  = auto\n| population_demonym      = {{lang-en|Aostan}} or Valdostan<br>{{lang-it|Valdostano}} (man)<br>{{lang-it|Valdostana}} (woman)<br>{{lang-fr|Vald\u00f4tain}} (man)<br>{{lang-fr|Vald\u00f4taine}} (woman)\n| population_note         = \n| population_blank1_title = Official languages<ref name=statut>{{cite web |title=Statut sp\u00e9cial de la Vallee d'Aoste|volume=Titre VI Art. 38 |year=2001 |publisher=Conseil r\u00e9gional de la Vall\u00e9e d'Aoste |language=fr |url=http://www.consiglio.regione.vda.it/statuto/statuto_f.asp |accessdate=2015-10-25 }}</ref>\n| population_blank1       = [[Italian language|Italian]], [[French language|French]]\n| demographics_type1      = Citizenship\n| demographics1_footnotes = <ref name=StatDemo>{{cite web|url=http://demo.istat.it/str2007/query.php?lingua=ita&Rip=S1&Reg=R02&Pro=P000&Com=&paese=A9999&submit=Tavola |title=Statistiche demografiche ISTAT |publisher=Demo.istat.it |date= |accessdate=2010-04-22|language=it}}</ref>\n| demographics1_title1    = Italian\n| demographics1_info1     = 95%\n| demographics1_title2    = \n| demographics1_info2     = \n| demographics1_title3    = \n| demographics1_info3     = \n| timezone1               = [[Central European Time|CET]]\n| utc_offset1             = +1\n| timezone1_DST           = [[Central European Summer Time|CEST]]\n| utc_offset1_DST         = +2\n| postal_code_type        = \n| postal_code             = \n| area_code_type          = [[ISO 3166 code]] \n| area_code               = IT-23 \n| blank_name_sec1         = [[List of Italian regions by GDP|GDP (nominal)]]\n| blank_info_sec1         = \u20ac4.4 billion (2017)<ref name=GDP>{{cite press release |url=https://ec.europa.eu/eurostat/documents/2995521/9618249/1-26022019-AP-EN.pdf/f765d183-c3d2-4e2f-9256-cc6665909c80 |title=Regional GDP per capita ranged from 31% to 626% of the EU average in 2017 |publisher=ec.europa.eu |accessdate=2 September 2019}}</ref>\n| blank1_name_sec1        = [[List of Italian regions by GDP|GDP per capita]]\n| blank1_info_sec1        = \u20ac35,200 (2017)<ref name=GDP/>\n| blank2_name_sec1         = [[Human Development Index|HDI]] (2017)\n| blank2_info_sec1         = 0.875<ref name=\"GlobalDataLab\">{{Cite web|url=https://hdi.globaldatalab.org/areadata/shdi/|title=Sub-national HDI - Area Database - Global Data Lab|website=hdi.globaldatalab.org|language=en|access-date=2018-09-13}}</ref><br/>{{color|green|very high}} \u00b7 [[List of Italian regions by Human Development Index|14th of 21]]\n| blank_name_sec2         = [[First-level NUTS of the European Union#Italy|NUTS Region]]\n| blank_info_sec2         = ITC\n| website                 = [http://www.regione.vda.it www.regione.vda.it]\n| footnotes               = \n}}\n\nThe '''Aosta Valley''' ({{lang-it|Valle d'Aosta}} {{IPA-it|\u02c8valle da\u02c8\u0254sta|}} (official) or {{lang|it|Val d'Aosta}} (usual); {{lang-fr|Vall\u00e9e d'Aoste}} {{IPA-fr|vale d\u0254st|}}<ref>[[Aostan French]] pronunciation - Jean-Marie Pierret, ''Phon\u00e9tique historique du fran\u00e7ais et notions de phon\u00e9tique g\u00e9n\u00e9rale'', Peeters, Louvain-la-Neuve, 1994, p.|104.</ref> (official) or {{lang|fr|Val d'Aoste}} (usual); {{lang-frp|Val d'Outa}} (usual); {{lang-wae|Augschtalann}} or {{lang|wae|Ougstalland}}; {{lang-pms|Val d'Osta}}) is a mountainous [[autonomous regions with special statute|autonomous]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.regione.vda.it/autonomia_istituzioni/lostatuto_f.aspx |title=Le Statut sp\u00e9cial de la Vall\u00e9e d'Aoste |date=1948 |accessdate=2017-07-10}} Articles 1 and 48b of the constitutional law officially assert the region's autonomy.</ref> [[Regions of Italy|region]] in northwestern [[Italy]]. It is bordered by [[Auvergne-Rh\u00f4ne-Alpes]], [[France]], to the west, [[Valais]], [[Switzerland]], to the north and by [[Piedmont]], [[Italy]], to the south and east. The regional [[Capital city|capital]] is [[Aosta]].\n\nCovering an area of {{convert|3263|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}} and with a population of about 128,000 it is the smallest, least populous, and least densely populated region of Italy. It is the only [[Italian regions|Italian region]] that is not sub-divided into provinces (the province of Aosta was dissolved in 1945).<ref name=\"camera.it\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.camera.it/_dati/leg13/lavori/bollet/200007/0718/pdf/06.pdf|title=Italian Parliament - VI Commission document 2000-07-18 (in Italian)}}</ref> Provincial administrative functions are provided by the regional government. The region is divided into 74 ''[[Comuni of the Aosta Valley|comuni]]'' ({{lang-fr|communes}}).\n\n[[Italian language|Italian]] and [[French language|French]] are the official languages,<ref name=statut/> though the native population also speak [[Vald\u00f4tain dialect|Vald\u00f4tain]], a dialect of [[Franco-Proven\u00e7al language|Arpitan (Franco-Proven\u00e7al)]]; 50.53% of the population can speak all three languages.<ref name=\"Vall\u00e9e d 2009, p. 20\">{{cite book |editor-last1=Decime |editor-first1=R. |editor-last2=Vernetto |editor-first2=G. |year=2009 |title=Profil de la politique linguistique de la Vall\u00e9e d'Aoste |publisher=Le Ch\u00e2teau |p=20 |language=fr }}</ref>\n\n==Geography==\n[[File:Champillon, Valpelline Valley (38437829771).jpg|thumb|left|200px|A view from refuge Champillon, [[Valpelline (valley)|Valpelline]]]]\nThe Aosta Valley is an Alpine valley which with its tributary valleys includes the Italian slopes of [[Mont Blanc]], [[Monte Rosa]], [[Gran Paradiso]] and the [[Matterhorn]]; its highest peak is [[Mont Blanc]] ({{cvt|4810|m|ft|disp=or}}). This makes it the highest region in Italy by [[list of Italian regions by highest point]].\n\n===Climate===\n\nThe valleys, usually above {{convert|1,600|m}}, annually have a Cold [[Continental climate|Continental Climate]] (''Dfc''). In this climate the snow season is very long, as long as 8 or 9 months at the highest points. During the summer, [[mist]] occurs almost every day. These areas are the wettest in the western Alps. Temperatures are low, between {{convert|-7|\u00b0C|0|abbr=on}} and {{convert|-3|\u00b0C|0|abbr=on}} in January, and in July between {{convert|20|\u00b0C|0|abbr=on}} and {{convert|35|\u00b0C|0|abbr=on}}. In this area is the town of [[Rh\u00eames-Notre-Dame]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Guida alla consultazione del bollettino meteorologico della Regione Autonoma Valle d'Aosta con elementi di meteorologia alpina |url=http://cf.regione.vda.it/download.php?fileID=74&lang=ita |publisher=Valle d'Aosta Official Website |language=it }}</ref> which may be the coldest town in the Western Alps and where the winter average temperature is around {{convert|-7|\u00b0C|0|abbr=on}}.{{citation needed|date=May 2016}}\n\nAreas between {{convert|2,000|and|3,500|m}} usually have a [[Tundra]] Climate ([[K\u00f6ppen climate classification#GROUP E: Polar climates|ET]]), where every month has an average temperature below {{convert|10|\u00b0C|0|abbr=on}}. This climate may be a kind of more severe Cold Oceanic Climate, with a low summer average but mild winters, sometimes above {{convert|-3|\u00b0C|0|abbr=on}}, especially near lakes, or a more severe Cold Continental Climate, with a very low winter average. Temperature averages in [[Plateau Rosa]], at {{convert|3400|m}} high, are {{convert|-11.6|\u00b0C|abbr=on}} in January and {{convert|1.4|\u00b0C|abbr=on}} in July. It is the coldest place in Italy where the climate is verifiable.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.meteoam.it/ta/infoStazione/LIMH | title=Tempo in atto su Plateau Rosa | publisher=meteoam.it | work=meteoam.it | accessdate=2020-01-21 | year=2012}}</ref>\n\nIn the past, above {{convert|3,500|m}}, all months had an average temperature below freezing, with a Perpetual Frost Climate (EF). In recent years though there was a rise in temperatures. See as an example the data for Plateau Rosa.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.meteoam.it/ta/infoStazione/LIMH | title=Tempo in atto su Plateau Rosa | publisher=meteoam.it | work=meteoam.it | accessdate=2020-01-21 | year=2012}}</ref>\n\n<gallery mode=\"packed\" heights=\"140\" style=\"font-size:88%;line-height:120%\">\nFile:Mont Blanc, Mont Maudit, Mont Blanc du Tacul.jpg|[[Mont Blanc]]\nFile:Cervino dal Lac Bleu.jpg|Lago Blu and the [[Matterhorn]]\nFile:Castor - Monte Castore.jpg|[[Castor (mountain)|Mount Castor]]\n</gallery>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Aosta.jpg|thumb|left|upright=1.1|View of [[Aosta]]]]\nThe first inhabitants of the Aosta Valley were [[Celts]] and [[Ligures]], whose [[Ligurian language (ancient)|language]] heritage remains in some local placenames. Rome conquered the region from the local [[Salassi]] around 25 BC and founded ''Augusta Pr\u00e6toria Salassorum'' (modern-day Aosta) to secure the strategic mountain passes, and they went on to build bridges and roads through the mountains. Thus, the name ''Valle d'Aosta'' literally means \"Valley of Augustus\".<ref>{{cite news | archive-date=July 19, 2012 | archive-url=https://archive.is/20120719045637/http://valdostadailytimes.com/features/x546438866/What-does-Valdosta-mean | title=What does Valdosta mean? | date=October 12, 2009 | last=Poling | first=Dean | periodical=Valdosta Daily Times | url=http://valdostadailytimes.com/features/x546438866/What-does-Valdosta-mean | accessdate=2013-02-21 | url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n[[File:The Astronomical Observatory of the Aosta Valley.jpg|thumb|right|The Astronomical Observatory of the Aosta Valley, in Saint-Barth\u00e9lemy ([[Nus]]).<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.eso.org/public/announcements/ann13044/ | title=ESO Astronomy Camp for Secondary School Students | work=eso.org | date=13 May 2013 | accessdate=15 May 2013}}</ref>]]\n\nIn 1031\u20131032, [[Humbert I of Savoy]], the founder of the [[House of Savoy]], received the title ''Count of Aosta'' from Emperor [[Conrad II, Holy Roman Emperor|Conrad II]] of the [[Franconia]]n line and built himself a [[Fort Bard|commanding fortification at Bard]]. Saint [[Anselm of Canterbury]] was born in Aosta in 1033 or 1034. The region was divided among strongly fortified [[castle]]s, and in 1191, [[Thomas I of Savoy]] found it necessary to grant to the communes a ''Charte des franchises'' (\"Charter of Liberties\") which preserved autonomy\u2014rights that were fiercely defended until 1770, when they were revoked in order to tie Aosta more closely to [[Piedmont]], but which were again demanded during post-Napoleonic times. In the mid-13th century, [[Frederick II, Holy Roman Emperor|Emperor Frederick II]] made the County of Aosta a [[duchy]] (see [[Duke of Aosta]]), and its arms charged with a lion rampant were carried in the [[Savoy]] arms until the reunification of Italy in 1870.<ref>{{cite web |author=Fran\u00e7ois Velde |year=2000 |title=Heraldry in the House of Savoia |url=http://www.heraldica.org/topics/national/italy1.htm |publisher=Heraldica |accessdate=2010-04-22}}</ref>\n\nThe region remained part of Savoy lands, with the exceptions of French occupations from 1539 to 1563, later in 1691, then between 1704 and 1706. It was also ruled by the [[First French Empire]] between 1800 and 1814. During French rule, it was part of Aoste [[arrondissement]] in [[Doire (department)|Doire]] department.<ref name=Gallica>[http://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k204214z/f388.image Almanach Imp\u00e9rial an bissextil MDCCCXII], pp. 392\u2013393, accessed in [[Gallica]] 18 February 2015 {{in lang|fr}}</ref> As part of the [[Kingdom of Sardinia]], it joined the new [[Kingdom of Italy]] in 1861.\n\nFrench forces briefly controlled the area at the end of [[World War II]], but withdrew under [[United Kingdom|British]] and [[United States|American]] pressure.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Harris |first1=Charles Reginald Schiller |title=Allied military administration of Italy, 1943-1945 |date=1957 |publisher=H. M. Stationery Office |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=Xks1AAAAIAAJ&q=|pages=318\u201320}}</ref> The region gained [[Autonomous regions with special statute (Italy)|special autonomous status]] after the end of World War II; the province of Aosta ceased to exist in 1945.<ref name=\"camera.it\"/>\n\n==Government and politics==\n{{Main|Politics of Aosta Valley}}\nFor more than 20 years the valley has been dominated by autonomist regional parties. The last [[Valdostan regional election, 2018|regional election]] was held in May 2018. On 27 June 2018 Nicoletta Spelgatti of the [[Lega Nord]] was elected president by the region's cabinet. She is the first woman and the first Lega Nord member to hold the position.<ref name=\"reg-it June2018\">{{cite news |title=Valle d'Aosta: Nicoletta Spelgatti (Lega) nuovo presidente Regione |url=http://www.regioni.it/riforme/2018/06/27/valle-daosta-nicoletta-spelgatti-lega-nuovo-presidente-regione-567702/ |work=Regioni.it |date=27 June 2018 |language=it}}</ref>\n\n==Demographics==\n\n{{multiple image\n| align = left\n| image1 = Bruil, Rhemes Valley (38406553102).jpg\n| width1 = 190\n| alt1 = \n| image2 = Casa Valdostana Cretaz Valtournenche.JPG\n| width2 = 200\n| footer = Typical Alpine houses in [[Rh\u00eames-Notre-Dame]] (left) and [[Valtournenche]] (right)\n}}\n{{Historical populations\n|type =\n|footnote = Source: [[Istituto Nazionale di Statistica|ISTAT]] 2001\n|1861 |81884\n|1871 |81260\n|1881 |85007\n|1901 |83529\n|1911 |80680\n|1921 |82769\n|1931 |83479\n|1936 |83455\n|1951 |94140\n|1961 |100959\n|1971 |109150\n|1981 |112353\n|1991 |115938\n|2001 |119548\n|2011 |128000\n|2017 |126883\n}}\n\nThe population density of Aosta Valley is by far the lowest of the Italian regions. In 2008, 38.9 inhabitants per km<sup>2</sup> were registered in the region, whereas the average national figure was 198.8, though the region has extensive uninhabitable areas of mountain and glacier, with a substantial part of the population living in the central valley. Migration from tributary valleys has now been stemmed by generous regional support for agriculture and tourist development. {{citation needed|date=October 2014}}\n\nThe population is growing slowly but steadily. Negative [[population growth]] since 1976 has been more than offset by immigration. The region has one of Italy's lowest [[birth rate]]s, with a rising average age. This, too, is partly compensated by immigration, since most immigrants arriving in the region are younger people working in the tourist industry. Between 1991 and 2001, the population of Aosta Valley grew by 3.1%, which is the highest growth among the Italian regions. With a negative natural population growth, this is due exclusively to positive net migration.<ref name=StatDemo/> Between 2001 and 2011, the population of Aosta Valley grew by a further 7.07%. {{As of|2006}}, the Italian [[National Institute of Statistics (Italy)|National Institute of Statistics]] (ISTAT) estimated that 4,976 foreign-born immigrants live in Aosta Valley, equal to 4.0% of the total regional population.\n\nThe [[Vald\u00f4tain]] population and their language dialects have been the subject of some sociological research.<ref>{{Cite journal |first=Chantal |last=Saint-Blancat |year=1984 |title=The Effect of Minority Group Vitality upon Its Sociopsychological Behaviour and Strategies |journal=Journal of Multilingual and Multicultural Development |volume=5 |issue=6 |pages=511\u2013516 |url=http://www.eric.ed.gov/ERICWebPortal/search/detailmini.jsp?_nfpb=true&_&ERICExtSearch_SearchValue_0=EJ313919&ERICExtSearch_SearchType_0=no&accno=EJ313919 |doi=10.1080/01434632.1984.9994177}}<br>{{Cite journal |last=Cooper |first=Danielle Chavy |year=1987 |title=Voices from the Alps: Literature in Val d'Aoste Today |journal=World Literature Today |volume=61 |issue=1 |pages=24\u201327 |jstor=40142443 |doi=10.2307/40142443 }}</ref>\n\n==Culture==\n===Languages===\n{{main|Aostan French|Vald\u00f4tain dialect}}\nThe Aosta Valley was the first government authority to adopt Modern French as the official language in 1536, three years before [[France]] itself.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Caniggia |first1=Mauro |last2=Poggianti |first2=Luca |date=2012-10-25 |title=La Vall\u00e9e d'Aoste: enclave francophone au sud-est du Mont Blanc |url=http://zigzag-francophonie.eu/ITALIE-Le-Val-d-Aoste |publisher=Zigzag magazine |language=fr |accessdate=2013-11-28 }}</ref> Italian and French are nowadays the region's [[official language]]s,<ref name=statut/> and are used for the regional government's acts and laws, though Italian is much more widely spoken in everyday life, and French is mostly spoken in cultural life. Education is conducted evenly in French and Italian,<ref name=statut/> so that anyone who has gone to school in the Aosta Valley can speak French to at least a medium-high level.<ref name=aostebi>{{cite web |author=AA. VV. |title=Une Vall\u00e9e d'Aoste bilingue dans une Europe plurilingue |others=in French and Italian |url=http://www.fondchanoux.org/scarica.aspx?id=29 |location=Aoste |publisher=Fondation Emile Chanoux |accessdate=2015-04-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924014323/http://www.fondchanoux.org/scarica.aspx?id=29 |archive-date=2015-09-24 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe [[regional language]], known as ''patou\u00e9 valdot\u00e8n'' or simply ''patou\u00e9'' (''valdostano'' in Italian, ''vald\u00f4tain'' in French), is a [[dialect|dialectal variety]] of [[Franco-Proven\u00e7al language|Franco-Proven\u00e7al]]. It is spoken as a [[native language|native]] and [[second language]] by 68,000 residents, or about 58% of the population according to a sociolinguistic survey carried out by the ''Fondation \u00c9mile Chanoux'' in 2001.<ref name=2001survey>{{Cite web|url=http://www.fondchanoux.org/sondaggiolinguisticod.aspx|title=Sondaggio linguistico: Q 0301 Lingua materna - Qual \u00e8 la sua lingua materna?|website=Fondation \u00c9mile Chanoux|language=it}}</ref>\n\nThe survey found out that the Italian language was spoken as a mother tongue by 77.29% of respondents, Franco-Proven\u00e7al by 17.91%, while French by 1.25%. The residents of the villages of [[Gressoney-Saint-Jean]], [[Gressoney-La-Trinit\u00e9]] and [[Issime]], in the [[Lys Valley]], speak two dialects of [[Walser German]], [[Titsch]] and [[T\u00f6itschu]], respectively.<ref name=\"aostebi\" /> According to the survey, [[Walser German]] was spoken as a mother tongue by 207 people, or 17.78%, in these three villages. Nevertheless, it was known to 56.38% of the population.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.fondchanoux.org/sondaggiolingusticowd.aspx|title=Sondaggio Linguistico Comunit\u00e0 Walser|website=Fondation \u00c9mile Chanoux|language=it}}</ref>\n\n{{bar box\n|title = Mother tongues in the Aosta Valley (2001)<ref name=2001survey/>\n|titlebar=#ddd |left1=  |right1= |float=left |width=350px\n|bars =\n{{bar percent|[[Italian language|Italian]]|green|77.29}}\n{{bar percent|[[Vald\u00f4tain]] ([[Franco-Proven\u00e7al]])|blue|17.91}}\n{{bar percent|[[Aostan French]]|red|1.25}}\n{{bar percent|Other languages|yellow|4.95}}\n}}{{bar box\n|title = Use of languages by the population (2001)<ref name=2001survey/>\n|titlebar=#ddd |left1=  |right1= |float=left |width=350px\n|bars =\n{{bar percent|[[Italian language|Italian]]|green|96.01}}\n{{bar percent|[[Aostan French]]|red|75.41}}\n{{bar percent|[[Vald\u00f4tain]] ([[Franco-Proven\u00e7al]])|blue|55.77}}\n{{bar percent|All three languages|yellow|50.53}}\n}}\n{{clear}}\n\n===Castles===\n[[File:Villeneuve Chatel Argent 02.jpg|thumb|right|[[Ch\u00e2tel-Argent]]]]\n[[File:11CastelloDiSaintPierre.jpg|thumb|The [[Saint-Pierre Castle]].<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20151228110543/http://museoscienze.it/?lang=en Aosta Valley Regional Museum of Natural Science] museoscienze.it</ref>]]\n[[File:Fenis Castle1.JPG|thumb|The [[F\u00e9nis Castle]], 13th century]]\nThere are a numerous medieval castles and fortified houses in the Aosta Valley, including [[Ch\u00e2tel-Argent]], [[Saint-Pierre Castle]], [[F\u00e9nis Castle]], [[Issogne Castle]], [[Ussel Castle]], [[Sarre Castle]], [[Cly Castle]], and [[Ch\u00e2telard Castle, Aosta Valley|Ch\u00e2telard Castle]].<ref name=mass>Massetti, E. [http://www.naturaosta.it/castles.htm \"Aosta Valley Castles\"] n.d., accessed 15 March 2014.</ref> [[Savoy Castle (Gressoney-Saint-Jean)|Savoy Castle]] in [[Gressoney-Saint-Jean]] was conceived in the 19th century and completed in 1904.<ref name=mass/> Since 1990, it has also been home to the [[Savoy Castle Alpine Botanical Garden]].\n\n===Cuisine===\nThe cuisine of Aosta Valley is characterized by simplicity and revolves around \"robust\" ingredients such as [[potato]]es, [[polenta]]; [[cheese]] and [[meat]]; and [[rye bread]]. Many of the dishes involve [[Fontina]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Fontina |url=http://www.lovevda.it/en/food-and-wine/products/cheese/fontina |publisher=Valle D'Aosta Official Tourism Website |year=2014 |accessdate=2015-10-23}}</ref> a cheese with [[Protected Geographical Status|PDO]] status, made from cow's milk that originates from the valley. It is found in dishes such as the soup ''\u00e0 la v\u00e2peuleun\u00e8ntse''<ref>{{cite web |title=Seupa \u00e0 la Vapelenentse (Valpelline Soup) |url=http://www.lovevda.it/en/food-and-wine/recipes/vapelenentse-soup |publisher=Valle D'Aosta Official Tourism Website |year=2014 |accessdate=2015-10-23}}</ref> ([[Valpelline, Aosta Valley|Valpelline]] Soup). Other cheeses made in the region are [[Toma cheese|Tomme de Gressoney]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Gressoney toma cheese |url=http://www.lovevda.it/en/food-and-wine/products/cheese/gressoney-toma|publisher=Aosta Valley Official Tourism Website |year=2014 |accessdate=2015-10-23}}</ref> and Seras. [[Valle d'Aosta Fromadzo|Fromadzo]] ([[Vald\u00f4tain]] for ''cheese'') has been produced locally since the 15th century and also has PDO status.<ref>{{cite web |title=Fromadzo cheese |url=http://www.lovevda.it/en/food-and-wine/products/cheese/fromadzo |publisher=Valle D'Aosta Official Tourism Website |year=2014 |accessdate=2015-10-23}}</ref>\n\nRegional specialities, besides Fontina, are ''Motzetta'' (dried [[chamois]] meat, prepared like [[prosciutto]]), [[Vall\u00e9e d'Aoste Lard d'Arnad]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Valle\u00e9 d'Aoste Lard d'Arnad |url=http://www.lovevda.it/en/food-and-wine/products/charcuterie/vallee-d-aoste-lard-d-arnad |publisher=Aosta Valley Official Tourism Website |year=2014 |accessdate=2015-10-23}}</ref> (a cured and brined [[fatback]] product with PDO designation), [[Vall\u00e9e d'Aoste Jambon de Bosses]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Vall\u00e9e d'Aoste Jambon de Bosses |url=http://www.lovevda.it/en/food-and-wine/products/charcuterie/vallee-d-aoste-jambon-de-bosses |publisher=Aosta Valley Official Tourism Website |year=2014 |accessdate=2015-10-23}}</ref> (a kind of [[ham]], likewise with PDO designation), and a black bread.\n\nNotable dishes include ''Carbonnade'', consisting of salt-cured beef cooked with onions and red wine served with [[polenta]]; breaded [[veal]] cutlets called ''costolette''; ''teuteuns'',<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.lovevda.it/en/food-and-wine/products/charcuterie/teuteun |title=The Teuteun |publisher=Valle D'Aosta Official Tourism Website |year=2014 |accessdate=2015-10-23 }}</ref> salt-cured cow's [[udder]] that is cooked and sliced; and ''steak \u00e0 la vald\u00f4taine'',<ref>{{cite web |title=Steak Valdaostan style |url=http://www.fontina-dop.it/ricetta_3_gb.html |publisher=Consorzio Produttori e Tutela Della Fontina DOP |language=it |accessdate=2015-10-23 }}</ref> a steak with [[cro\u00fbton]]s, ham and melted cheese.\n\n===Wine growing===\n{{See also|Valle d'Aosta DOC}}\nNotable wines include two white wines from [[Morgex]] (''Blanc de Morgex et de La Salle'' and ''Chaudelune''), a red wine blend from Arvier (''Enfer d'Arvier'') and one from [[Gamay]].<ref>{{cite web |title=D.O.C. Wine |url=http://www.lovevda.it/en/food-and-wine/wines |publisher=Valle D'Aosta Official Tourism Website |year=2014 |accessdate=2015-10-23 }}</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery mode=\"packed\" heights=\"130\" style=\"font-size:88%;line-height:120%\">\nFile:Sito archeologico di Chenal 1120484.JPG|The prehistoric site near Chenal castle, [[Montjovet]], rich in [[petroglyph]]\nFile:La Thuile-Rifugio Deffeyes 2.jpg|A view from refuge Albert Deffeyes, [[La Thuile, Italy|La Thuile]]\nFile:Capra ibex gran paradiso.jpg|Male [[Alpine Ibex]] in [[Gran Paradiso National Park]]\nFile:Marmotta alpina (Marmota marmota).jpg| [[Alpine marmot]] in [[Gran Paradiso National Park]]\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Italy|European Union}}\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[Alps-Mediterranean Euroregion]]\n* [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Aosta]]\n* [[Elections in Aosta Valley]]\n* [[Mont Blanc]]\n* [[List of Presidents of Aosta Valley]]\n* [[Arch of Augustus (Aosta)|Arch of Augustus in Aosta]]\n* [[Roman Theatre, Aosta]]\n* [[Pont d'A\u00ebl|Roman bridge Pont d'A\u00ebl]]\n* [[Bridge of Grand Arvou|13th-century bridge of Grand Arvou]]\n* [[Fort Bard|Fort Bard\u2014Museum of the Alps]]\n* [[Mont Blanc Tunnel]]\n* [[Gran Paradiso National Park]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Sources==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{Cite journal | last=Cerutti | first=Augusta Vittoria | title=Le Pays de la Doire et son peuple | publisher=\u00e9diteur Musumeci | location=[[Quart, Italy|Quart]] | year=| isbn=| page= }}\n* {{Cite journal | last=Colliard | first=Lin | title=La culture vald\u00f4taine au cours des si\u00e8cles | location=Aoste | year=1976 | isbn=| page= }}\n* {{Cite journal | last=Henry | first=Joseph-Marie | title=Histoire de la Vall\u00e9e d'Aoste | publisher=Imprimerie Marguerettaz | location=Aoste | year=1967 | isbn=| page= }}\n* {{Cite journal | last=Janin | first=Bernard | title=Le Val d'Aoste. Tradition et renouveau | publisher=\u00e9diteur Musumeci | location=[[Quart, Italy|Quart]] | year=1976 | isbn=| page= }}\n* {{Cite journal | last=Riccarand | first=Elio | title=Storia della Valle d'Aosta contemporanea (1919-1945) | publisher=Stylos Aoste | location=Aoste | year=| isbn=| page= }}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikivoyage|Aosta Valley}}\n{{Commons|Aosta Valley}}\n* [http://www.regione.vda.it/ Website of the Aosta Valley Regional Authority] (in Italian and French)\n** [http://www.regione.vda.it/imagevallee/default_i.asp Photo gallery of the Aosta Valley]\n** [http://cf.regione.vda.it/ Weather forecast and map of the Aosta Valley]\n* [http://www.mondimedievali.net/Castelli/valdaosta.htm Castes and fortresses] at mondimedievali.net {{in lang|it}}\n\n{{Aosta Valley|nocat=yes}}\n{{Comuni of Aosta Valley|nocat=yes}}\n{{Regions of Italy}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Aosta Valley| ]]\n[[Category:Autonomous regions of Italy]]\n[[Category:Arpitany]]\n[[Category:Provinces of Italy]]\n[[Category:Regions of Italy]]\n[[Category:Valleys of Italy]]\n[[Category:Valleys of the Alps]]\n[[Category:Castles in Aosta Valley]]\n[[Category:French-speaking countries and territories]]\n[[Category:NUTS 2 statistical regions of the European Union]]\n[[Category:Regions of Europe with multiple official languages]]\n[[Category:Wine regions of Italy]]\n", "name_user": "CAPTAIN RAJU", "label": "safe", "comment": "linkAntonio FossonusingFind link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aosta_Valley"}
{"title_page": "2014 SIU Edwardsville Cougars men's soccer team", "text_new": "{{Advert|date=June 2018}}\n{{Infobox NCAA team season\n|year=2014\n|team=SIU Edwardsville Cougars\n|sport=Soccer\n|image=SIU Edwardsville Cougars wordmark.svg\n|image_size=250\n|conference=Missouri Valley Conference\n|division=\n|short_conf= MVC\n|CoachRank=\n|APRank=\n|record= 8\u20139\u20134\n|conf_record= 4\u20131\u20131\n|head_coach= Brian Jones & David Korn (Co-head)\n|hc_year = 1st\n|asst_coach1= \n|asst_coach2= Scott Gyllenborg\n|asst_coach3=  \n|asst_coach4=\n|stadium= [[Ralph Korte Stadium]]<br>Capacity, 4,000\n|champion= MVC Tournament Champions\n|tourney= NCAA Division I Men's Soccer Tournament<br>2nd Round\n|tourney_result=\n}}\n{{2014 Missouri Valley Conference men's soccer standings}}\nThe '''2014 SIU Edwardsville Cougars men's soccer team''' represents [[Southern Illinois University Edwardsville]] during the [[2014 NCAA Division I men's soccer season]]. The Cougars are coached in 2014 by co-head coaches Brian Jones and David Korn. The team plays their home games on Bob Guelker Field at the [[Ralph Korte Stadium]] as an affiliate member of the [[Missouri Valley Conference]] (MVC).<ref>[http://www.siuecougars.com/sports/m-soccer/index SIUE]</ref>\n\n==Preseason==\nFourteen players returned from the 8-9-2 team of 2013, including two first team All-Missouri Valley Conference performers: forward [[Christian Volesky]] and defender [[Matt Polster]]; All-MVC Honorable Mention defender Justin Bilyeu; and  MVC All-Freshmen defenders  Andrew Kendall-Moulin and [[Austin Ledbetter]] . They were joined by five [[Redshirt (college sports)|\"redshirted\"]] freshmen who were in the group that was named one of the nation's top recruiting classes of 2013,<ref>[http://www.topdrawersoccer.com/college-soccer-articles/final-2013-mens-recruiting-class-rankings_aid28901 Final 2013 men\u2019s recruiting class rankings | College Soccer<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> a redshirted junior, a transfer who was First Team All-Conference in [[The Summit League]],<ref>[http://www.thesummitleague.org/sports/msoc/2013-14/releases/201311123b9itw Summit League Announces Men\u2019s Soccer Awards - The Summit League<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> and five freshmen.<ref name=\"roster\">[http://www.siuecougars.com/sports/m-soccer/2014-15/roster 2014 SIUE Men's Soccer Roster - SIUE<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> The six member incoming 2014 class, like its predecessor, was rated one of the top recruiting classes in the country.<ref>[http://www.collegesoccernews.com/index.php/recuiting/top-40-recruiting-classes/121-2014/603-2014-top-recruiting-classes 2014 Top 40 Recruiting Classes - CollegeSoccerNews.com<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> SIUE is the only Division I team with 100% of its 2013 scoring players back for 2014.\n\nFor the second season in a row, defender Matt Polster was one of 32 players named to the preseason watch list for the [[Missouri Athletic Club]]\u2019s [[Hermann Trophy]], college soccer's highest individual award.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nscaatv.com/news/2014/08/2014-mac-hermann-watch-lists |title=2014 MAC Hermann Watch Lists<!-- Bot generated title --> |access-date=2014-08-20 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140821052625/http://www.nscaatv.com/news/2014/08/2014-mac-hermann-watch-lists |archive-date=2014-08-21 |url-status=dead|df= }}</ref>\n\nIn [[TopDrawerSoccer.com|Top Drawer Soccer]]'s (TDS) preseason list of the top 100 college soccer players in the nation, Mat Polster was ranked #48.<ref>[http://www.topdrawersoccer.com/college-soccer-articles/college-soccer-preseason-top-100-players_aid33551 College Soccer Preseason Top 100 Players | College Soccer<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>  Additionally, the TDS preseason rankings of the top 20 players in each conference ranked Polster  #2, Christian Volesky #3, Andrew Kendall-Moullin #17, and Justin Bilyeu #18 in the MVC.<ref name=autogenerated1>[http://www.topdrawersoccer.com/college-soccer/college-conference-top-20/men College Soccer Player Rankings<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nIn the MVC preseason coaches' poll, SIUE was picked to finish fifth. Seniors Matt Polster and Christian Volesky were named to the pre-season All-MVC team, Polster for the third season in a row, Volesky for the second.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.mvc-sports.com/msoccer/news/2014-15/7453/defending-champ-missouri-state-picked-to-win-mvc-mens-soccer-crown/ |title=Missouri Valley Conference - Defending Champ Missouri State Picked to Win MVC Men's Soccer Crown<!-- Bot generated title --> |access-date=2014-08-20 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141031232536/http://www.mvc-sports.com/msoccer/news/2014-15/7453/defending-champ-missouri-state-picked-to-win-mvc-mens-soccer-crown/ |archive-date=2014-10-31 |url-status=dead|df= }}</ref>\n\nIn exhibition games, the Cougars defeated the [[Oakland Golden Grizzlies men's soccer|Oakland Golden Grizzlies]] 3\u20131 at Korte Stadium  and the  [[IUPUI Jaguars men's soccer|IUPUI Jaguars]] 2\u20130 in Indianapolis.\n\n==Season==\n\nFormer coach [[Scott Donnelly (coach)|Scott Donnelly]] set up a demanding schedule which included five teams that were ranked during the 2013 season,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://new.nscaatv.com/rankings/college |title=NSCAA/Continental Tire Rankings<!-- Bot generated title --> |access-date=2014-06-11 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140410110703/http://new.nscaatv.com/rankings/college |archive-date=2014-04-10 |url-status=dead|df= }}</ref> four that were in the NCAA Tournament.<ref>[https://www.ncaa.com/interactive-bracket/soccer-men/d1 2013 Division I Men's Soccer Tournament | NCAA.com<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> There was also a full Missouri Valley Conference schedule and matches against traditional rivals.<ref name=\"sched\">[http://www.siuecougars.com/sports/m-soccer/2014-15/schedule 2014 SIUE Men's Soccer Schedule - SIUE<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nOpening the season at home for the first time since 2010, the Cougars outplayed the Virginia Tech Hokies through regulation time in a game that featured outstanding goalkeeping on both ends of the field. Despite SIUE dominating the shooting 16\u20138, Tech's Brad Vorv found himself free and lofted a 25' shot past Kent Kobernus in the 97th minute, giving the Hokies the \"golden goal\" victory.<ref>[http://www.hokiesports.com/msoccer/recaps/20140829aaa.html Hokies open season with 1-0 OT win over SIUE<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nOn a day dominated by the heat, with the game punctuated with several water breaks, SIUE and Tulsa missed numerous scoring opportunities, especially on set pieces. The Cougars scored first, with Scheipeter passing up a contested shot to hit Volesky, who faced the open net. A Cougars turnover started the action that led to the Golden Hurricane's Neil putting in a shot from a difficult angle to tie the game. Despite the two sides taking 35 shots (Tulsa leading 23\u201312), the game was mainly a defensive struggle, remaining tied at one goal apiece through regulation and the first extra time period. Cougar goalkeeper Kobernus made his eighth save on another shot by Neil, but when he failed to corral the ball, Barrett put the rebound into the net to give Tulsa the double-overtime \"golden goal\" win.<ref>[http://www.tulsahurricane.com/sports/m-soccer/recaps/083114aaa.html Tulsa's Barrett Scores in 101st Minute for Double-Overtime Win - Tulsa Official Athletic Site<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nPlaying a mid-week game at Memphis, the Cougars dominated early play, with Volesky scoring off a pass from Garet Christianson. As play went on, SIUE seemed to grow complacent and careless, passing beyond intended teammates, directly at defenders, or to no one in particular. As such play continued, the Tigers gained confidence and took control in the last ten minutes of the first half.  Memphis remained in control through the second half, with Khulfan scoring on a breakaway and the Tigers outshooting the Cougars 8\u22124 for the half. SIUE seemed to be back in control in their third extra time game in three matches. They outshot the Tigers 4\u20130 in the first overtime period and took the first shot of the second OT. But Ledbetter then drew his second yellow card and was ejected. Memphis, a man up, immediately applied the pressure and scored only 23 seconds after the red card, giving the Cougars their third \"golden goal\" loss in three games.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.gotigersgo.com/sports/m-soccer/recaps/090314aab.html |title=Men's Soccer Defeats SIU-Edwardsville in Home Opener - GOTIGERSGO.COM - The Official Website of the University of Memphis Tigers<!-- Bot generated title --> |access-date=2014-09-04 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140904135256/http://www.gotigersgo.com/sports/m-soccer/recaps/090314aab.html |archive-date=2014-09-04 |url-status=dead|df= }}</ref>\n\nHosting undefeated Butler in the first-ever meeting between the two programs, the Cougars set a school record with four consecutive extra time games for the first time in the program's 48-year history. SIUE dominated play in the first half, with Volesky scoring on a pass in the box from Hackett. On Butler's only first half threat, Kendall-Moulin fouled the Bulldog's Goldsmith in the box, with Postlewait scoring on the penalty kick. Butler came out on the offensive to start the second half, taking the first three shots, but the Cougars took charge again, yet were unable to get anything past the Bulldog's goalkeeper. In the first extra period, an SIUE player was fouled amidst a crowd directly in front of the goal mouth; the Cougar's best winning chance of the young season went astray as Volesky's penalty kick bounced off the post and away. The two sides traded possessions, with both defenses turning aside repeated attacks through the second extra time period, and the game ended with SIUE getting its first point of the season on a frustrating draw.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://butlersports.com/sports/m-soccer/2014-15/releases/20140907bbrcv9 |title=Butler, SIUE Play To 1-1 Draw - Butler<!-- Bot generated title --> |access-date=2014-09-11 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140911091016/http://butlersports.com/sports/m-soccer/2014-15/releases/20140907bbrcv9 |archive-date=2014-09-11 |url-status=dead|df= }}</ref>\n\nIn a mid-week road game, the Cougars once more dominated early play, and Volesky scored his fourth goal in five games off a pass from Garet Christianson. The 'Roos had managed only a couple of long-distance shots before an uncharacteristic turnover by Polster left his SIUE teammates out of position, and UMKC scored an easy tying shot on a rebound of a missed first shot. Sloppy passing and an inability to either score on set pieces or cleanly clear the ball from the defensive end have continued to be a problem at odds with SIUE's strong soccer tradition. Repeated failures to clear set up a second UMKC goal, putting the Cougars into a position of trailing in the score during regulation time for the first time this season. Repeated failures to score on corner kick after corner kick and a Polster penalty kick that was saved by the 'Roos' goalkeeper, McGaughey, left the Cougars with one more loss.<ref>[http://www.umkckangaroos.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_LANG=C&ATCLID=209644603&DB_OEM_ID=18300 'Roos Come From Behind in Home Opening Victory Over SIUE - UMKC Athletics<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nTrying for a change in results, the Cougars resorted to changing from single-color uniforms to face DePaul at Korte Stadium. One thing that did change was the early game dominance by SIUE, who surrendered the first goal for the first time since the season opener, when Hunter's rocket of a pass hit Megally just outside the six yard box for an easy shot past a diving Kobernus. The Blue Demons outshot the Cougars in the first half, but SIUE picked up the action after halftime. In the sixtieth minute, Bilyeu fired a pass to a wide-open Ellis, who lofted a chip shot over the DePaul keeper to even the score. Both defenses repeatedly turned aside their opponent, and the match went into extra time for the fifth time in the Cougars' six games. SIUE escaped disaster when the defense held against a free kick from just outside the six yard box after Kobernus fouled by picking up a ball a Cougar had kicked to him, and the first extra period ended with the score still at 1\u20131. The Cougars stepped up the pressure further in the second overtime period, but DePaul's keeper and defense withstood the onslaught, and the game ended a draw, SIUE's second.<ref>[http://www.depaulbluedemons.com/sports/m-soccer/recaps/091314aaa.html Megally's Early Goal Leads to 1-1 Double OT Tie at SIU-Edwardsville - DePaul University Official Athletic Site<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nOpening a two-game road trip against ranked Pac-12 teams in California, the Cougars once again scored first against #24 Stanford, with Volesky tapping a loose ball to Polster in the box. Twenty minutes later, the Cardinal's Morris went to the post, drawing Kobernus to him, then tapped a pass to Glover for the tying goal. Stanford was the dominant team in the first half, outshooting the Cougars and taking several corners to the Cougars' none. On a corner kick, the Cardinal's Skundrich fired into the box to the head of Vincent, who scored the go-ahead goal. In the second half, The Cougars outplayed the Cardinal early and late, while Stanford had the better of the middle, but neither side was able to get a shot past the other's keeper, and the home team picked up the win in a game that was much closer than the two teams' records might indicate.<ref>[http://www.gostanford.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=30600&ATCLID=209665040 Stanford Battles Back - GoStanford.com<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nOn a Sunday afternoon in Berkeley, the Cougars played another closely contested match at the home of a ranked opponent, the #15 California Golden Bears, Cal scored first when Bonomo intercepted a pass in SIUE's defensive end, putting him one-on-one with Kobernus, and he scored in the 17th minute. Only four and a half minutes later, Hallisey passed to Carrera-Garcia and kept going, with Carrera-Garcia completing the give-and-go back to Hallisey and putting the Golden Bears up 2-0. SIUE had an opportunity to close the gap when the Cal goalkeeper committed a foul inside the box, but  Volesky's shot was off the crossbar, and his rebound attempt was wide. The Cougars once again outshot their opponent only to have the other side's goalkeeper make repeated saves, but in the 77th minute, Polster played the ball in to Volesky, who tallied his fifth goal of the season. In another match that was tighter than the opponents' records show, SIUE came out on the short end and head into the MVC schedule while still in search of their first victory.<ref>[http://www.calbears.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=30100&ATCLID=209667851 No. 15 Cal Wins Its Fifth Consecutive Match, Beats SIUE 2-1 - California Golden Bears - University of California Official Athletic Site<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nOpening the MVC season on a Monday night in Evansville, the Cougars managed to accomplish three things they had not done since the preseason---keep a clean sheet, score more than one goal, and win a game. As has often been the case, SIUE dominated play, outshooting the Purple Aces 8 to 3 in the first half and 7 to 3 in the second, with only 2 of Evansville's shots being on goal and both of those saved by Kobernus. The Cougars got on the scoreboard when Volesky was taken down in the box by the Aces' keeper in the 33rd minute; Garet Christianson put the penalty kick into the open left side of the net. In the second half, briefly Evansville put on a strong showing that resulted in four consecutive corner kicks, but the SIUE defense held off the assault. In the 73rd minute, Polster found a loose ball near the top of the 18 yard box and buried it in the right side of the net to double the lead. The Cougars kept trying for additional scoring, but Evansville's keeper held firm, and SIUE had to be satisfied with the 2\u20130 victory.<ref>[http://www.gopurpleaces.com/news/2014/9/29/MSOC_0929140751.aspx Evansville Athletics - Men's Soccer drops MVC season opener 2-0 to SIUE<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nIn front of a huge Homecoming crowd at Korte Stadium, the Cougars recorded their second consecutive two-goal shutout win. SIUE's defense held off Bradley's MVC-leading offense while the offense outshot the Braves 11\u20136. After the Cougars had been 0\u2013for\u2013the\u2013season on set plays, in the 18th minute, Kendall-Moulin tapped a corner to Bilyeu who tapped it right back to Kendal-Moulinn, whose crossing pass found Volesky's head for the first goal. Eighteen minutes later, inside the eighteen yard box, Volesky passed to Hoguet, who had just entered the game and fired blazing shot into the corner of the net on his first touch. Through the remainder of the game, the Cougars continued to press for additional scoring while their defense frustrated the Braves repeatedly. After two conference games, SIUE and Missouri State sit atop the MVC standings with 2\u20130\u20130 records.<ref>[http://www.bradleybraves.com//ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=3400&ATCLID=209697513 SIUE Blanks Bradley Soccer, 2-0 - BRADLEYBRAVES.COM\u2014Official Web Site of Bradley University Athletics<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nSIUE's third conference game was in Conway, Arkansas, the home of the MVC's other associate member, Central Arkansas. Despite periods of poor passing, the Cougars managed to dominate another opponent, outshooting the Bears in the first half 7\u20131. UCA's keeper was able to stop all of the Cougars' shots on goal, and the teams went to the locker room tied at nil. The home team stepped up their intensity in the second half, and outshot the Cougars 8\u20133. But, in the 60th minute, Polster crossed to Danzy, who headed home his first goal of the season. Less than thirteen minutes, Houget hit a long pass to a breaking Garet Christianson; with the UCA keeper coming out, Christianson got to the ball first and nailed the goal from 25 yards out. The Bears got on the board in the 83rd minute when, on a free kick from just outside the box, a Cougar fouled in the box to set up a penalty kick. Kobernus saved on the PK but was unable to control the rebound that was tapped in by Moquete from 5 yards out. It took the Cougars only 36 seconds to go back up by two; the ball was smoothly played into the UCA end, Ellis crossed to Danzy, and the redshirt junior collected his second goal of the game. After the frustrating start of the season, SIUE has a three-game winning streak and sits alone atop the MVC standings.<ref>[http://ucasports.com/news/2014/10/11/MSOC_1011142758.aspx Central Arkansas Athletics - UCA MEN FALL TO SIUE 3-1<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nThe Cougars were inhospitable hosts to Drake and played a game of almost total dominance en route to a 4\u20130 shellacking. Five minutes into the game, Bilyeu took a pass from Kendall-Moullin and fired a high, looping shot from 35 yards out that sank into the top right corner of the net over the Bulldog keeper's reaching hands. On a corner kick in the 37th minute, Drake's keeper turned awy the ball, but Polster found the rebound 4 yards out and buried it, giving SIUE a two-goal lead. Four minutes later, Volesky took a long pass in the open, juked the keeper, then passed off to an even more open Christianson, who put the Cougars up 3\u20130 for the first time in the season. Drake managed to fire off two shots that were high and wide late in the half, and the home squad went to the locker room up by three after outshooting the Bulldogs 7\u20132. The domination continues in the second half as the Cougars outshot the visitors 8\u20130 while eight subs saw action. In the 59th minute, Volesky drove into the box, stumbled and fell, picked himself up, regained the ball, and scored his MVC leading seventh goal of the season. That goal gave SIUE, now 4\u20130\u20130 in MVC games, its widest margin of victory in a conference game since joining the league in 2010. The Cougar win, combined with the Missouri State draw at Loyola, extended their lead in the Valley standings to five points.<ref>[http://www.godrakebulldogs.com/ViewArticle.dbml?SPID=8125&DB_OEM_ID=15700&ATCLID=209724591 Bulldogs Fall At SIU Edwardsville, 4-0 - GoDrakeBulldogs.com\u2014Official Web site of Drake University Athletics<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nOn a Wednesday night in DeKalb, the Cougars started strong but seemed to be continually out of sync without the presence of leading scorer, Christian Volesky. SIUE got off the first four shots of the game and outshot NIU 7\u20134 in the first half. In the eighth minute, Danzy found himself facing an open net but fired wide. In the 17th minute, Danzy went into the box as Christianson shot, but found himself decked by the Huskies' keeper, hustling out for the save. Danzy atoned for what had gone before when he found himself again facing an open goal, driving Ledbetter's pass from behind the defense into the net. Less than a minute and a half later though, it was the Huskies who forced the action, earning a corner kick that Hall drove in a high slicing arc that Kobernus was only able to get a hand on as it sailed into the net for an [[Olympic goal|\"olimpico\"]] goal to knot the score. The Cougars outshot the Huskies 5\u20134 in the second half, but only one SIUE shot was on goal, while not only were all of NIU's shots on goal, Kobernus was able to save only one. The SIUE defense turned back repeated NIU challenges only to see the front line give the ball right back to the home squad. The Huskies took advantage,  scoring three second half goals, and the final 4\u20131 score was the widest victory margin for a Cougars' opponent since SIUE returned to Division I in 2008.<ref>[http://www.niuhuskies.com/sports/m-soccer/recaps/102214aaa.html Offense Explodes as Huskies Hammer SIUE - NIUHUSKIES.COM - The Northern Illinois Official Athletic Site<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nOn a Tuesday night at Louisville's brand new, state-of-the-art stadium, the defenses were at the forefront of the action. The Cardinals outshot the Cougars, but most of their shoots were from long-distance and went high and/or wide. Both defenses repeatedly turned away everything that came at them, and the game turned into the Cougar's sixth overtime game of the season. At the end of 110 minutes of furious action, SIUE had played the  #22 ranked Cardinals to a 0\u20130 draw.<ref>[http://www.gocards.com/sports/m-soccer/recaps/102814aaa.html No. 9 Cardinals Draw with SIU Edwardsville - GoCards.com | Official Website of University of Louisville Athletics<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nOn a frigid Saturday night at Korte, the Cougars played the Missouri State Bears for possession of first place in the MVC. As expected, the defenses dominated the game, with both teams spending much time trying to maintain possession of the ball, then attacking and being turned aside. In the 24th minute, only seconds after making a solid save, Kobernus was caught out of position as the Bears' Roberts chipped a shot over him and into the net to give State the lead. As time ran down in the first  half, Volesky was fouled hard about 25 yards out. Bilyeu fired the free kick into the box, and Volesky headed in his league-leading eighth goal of the season to knot the score 1\u20131 with 0:11 on the clock. The second half was another defensive showcase, with both sides shutting out the other.  With regulation time ending tied at 1\u20131, the Cougars tied the school record for most overtime games in a season, with 7 for the third time in four years. Two ten-minute extra-time periods ended with the score still 1\u20131, SIUE still leading the MVC, while Missouri State dropped to third place.<ref>[http://www.missouristatebears.com/sports/m-soccer/recaps/110114aaa.html MSU and SIUE Draw, Set Up Huge Final Men's Soccer Weekend - Missouri State University Official Athletic Site<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nThe Cougars traveled to Charleston for a Tuesday afternoon game in the rain and mud at Eastern Illinois. SIUE dominated almost every facet of the game except goalkeeping. Outshooting the Panthers 18\u20138 and 12\u20136 on goal, the Cougars saw EIU's keeper, Novotny, make 8 saves while Kobernus saved only 3. The offense did get three shots past Eastern's keeper during regulation time, including 2 by junior Lane (only the 2nd and 3rd of his career), and, the score was tied at 3 after 90 minutes. In their school record eighth OT game of the year, the Cougars, playing several non-regulars, went into a second extra period before senior Bauman collected his first career goal and give SIUE their first road victory of the season.<ref>[http://www.eiupanthers.com/news/2014/11/4/MSOC_1104142416.aspx Eastern Illinois Panthers - Men's Soccer Falls In Double Overtime<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nThe last game of the regular season was at Loyola in Chicago on a Saturday night. Defense was once more the feature, with both sides repeatedly denying scoring chances by taking the ball away before the offenses could set up to shoot.  The Ramblers D was quite physical, resulting in 17 called fouls and 2 yellow cards along with many other plays that could have been called; SIUE was called for only 6 fouls, but Hoguet was booked for committing a hard foul after being twice taken down in the box without a foul being called. The Cougars outshot Loyola 6\u20132, but a Ramblers' counterattack in the 33rd minute caught Kobernus off the line, forcing him to come further out to challenge Bement, who then scored from 15 yards out. SIUE thought they had evened the score in the 89th minute; Bilyeu's shot rattled around in the net, and the Cougars were well into celebrating when the goal was waved off on an offside call made well after the play. With Missouri State defeating Evansville 1\u20130, SIUE dropped to second place in the final MVC standings and the #2 seed in the MVC tournament.<ref>[http://www.loyolaramblers.com/sports/m-soccer/recaps/110814aaa.html Ramblers Prevail, 1-0, On Senior Night Over SIU-Edwardsville Loyola University Chicago Official Athletic Site<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nThe '''MVC Awards''' were announced at the banquet held on the evening between the tournament quarterfinals and semifinals. '''Christian Volesky''' was named ''MVC Player of the Year'' and '''Mat Polster''' was named ''MVC Defensive Player of the Year''; both were named to the ''MVC All-Conference First Team'' for the third season in a row. '''Justin Bilyeu''' and '''Kent Kobernus''' were named to the ''MVC All-Conference Second Team''. '''Garet Christianson''', '''Andrew Kendall-Moullin''', and '''Austin Ledbetter''' were awarded ''MVC All-Conference Honorable Mention'' citations.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.mvc-sports.com/msoccer/news/2014-15/7636/2014-mvc-mens-soccer-all-conference-teams-announced/#.VGa9sPnF-So |title=Missouri Valley Conference - 2014 MVC Men's Soccer All-Conference Teams Announced<!-- Bot generated title --> |access-date=2014-11-15 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141119225950/http://www.mvc-sports.com/msoccer/news/2014-15/7636/2014-mvc-mens-soccer-all-conference-teams-announced/#.VGa9sPnF-So |archive-date=2014-11-19 |url-status=dead|df= }}</ref>\n\n==Postseason==\nWith the 2nd seed and a first round bye, the Cougars entered MVC Tournament play in the semis versus 6th seed Bradly on the Braves' home turf. Although SIUE mostly dominated possession and play (outshooting BU 27\u20137), Bradley took the lead in the 22nd minute when, on a counterattack, Lofgren headed in a near-perfect crossing pass. The Cougars kept pressing the action against the Braves' close-checking defense, and in the 78th minute, Bradley was called for a clearly seen shove in the box. Bilyeu buried the penalty kick to tie the match. In the 85th minute, Kendall-Moulin loosed a free kick from near mid-field that arrowed straight to Danzy, who slipped a shot past the diving keeper to give SIUE the lead. Although Bradley tried to press for a tying goal, the Cougar defense held firm, and earned a place in the tourney finals and a rematch with MVC regular season champion Missouri State.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.mvc-sports.com/msoccer/news/2014-15/7663/msoc-championship-siue-2-bradley-1/#.VGbL0PnF-So |title=Missouri Valley Conference - MSOC Championship: SIUE 2, Bradley 1<!-- Bot generated title --> |access-date=2014-11-15 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129023706/http://www.mvc-sports.com/msoccer/news/2014-15/7663/msoc-championship-siue-2-bradley-1/#.VGbL0PnF-So |archive-date=2014-11-29 |url-status=dead|df= }}</ref>\n\nThe MVC Championship game saw the defenses of SIUE and Missouri State repeatedly stifle the other squad's best offensive efforts. The Cougars took more shots, 17\u20139, but the Bears had more shots on goal, 7\u20134. As in their first meeting, the two teams went into double-overtime (another new SIUE record\u2013 9th OT game of the year). In the 108th minute, on an [[ESPN]] Top 10 play, Kendall-Moullin drove a free kick to the left of the goal. Danzy leapt above the crowd and headed the ball into the right side of the net to give the Cougars their first MVC Tournament Championship and send SIUE to the [[NCAA Division I Men's Soccer Championship]] tournament for the first time since 1982.<ref name=\"MVC\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.mvc-sports.com/msoccer/news/2014-15/7668/siue-wins-first-ever-mens-soccer-championship/#.VGkjhvnF-So |title=Missouri Valley Conference - SIUE Win's First-Ever Men's Soccer Championship<!-- Bot generated title --> |access-date=2014-11-16 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129033608/http://www.mvc-sports.com/msoccer/news/2014-15/7668/siue-wins-first-ever-mens-soccer-championship/#.VGkjhvnF-So |archive-date=2014-11-29 |url-status=dead|df= }}</ref>\n\nAt the conclusion of the conference tournament, '''Jabari Danzy''' was named ''MVC Tournament MVP'' and was joined on the ''2014 MVC Men's Soccer All-Tournament Team'' by teammates '''Justin Bilyeu''', '''Kent Kobernus''', and '''Matt Polster'''.<ref name=\"MVC\"/>  For his efforts, '''Danzy''' was also named to the Team of the Week for both ''Top Drawer Soccer''<ref>[http://www.topdrawersoccer.com/college-soccer-articles/mens-team-of-the-week:-nov-10-16_aid35432 Men\u2019s Team of the Week: Nov. 10-16 | College Soccer<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> and ''College Soccer News''.<ref>[http://www.collegesoccernews.com/index.php/awards/team-of-the-week/708-college-soccer-news-national-team-of-the-week-week-ending-november-16-2015 College Soccer News National Team Of The Week - Week Ending November 16, 2015 - CollegeSoccerNews.com<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nOn Monday, November 17, the tournament brackets were announced. SIUE was slated to meet Northwestern in Evanston, with the winner traveling to play the #15 seed, California.<ref>[https://www.ncaa.com/interactive-bracket/soccer-men/d1 2014 Division I Men's Soccer Tournament | NCAA.com<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.thetelegraph.com/news/collegesports-home_top-localsports-sports/50715456/Previous-owners-return |title=They\u2019re baaack: Cougars return to NCAA Div. I soccer nationals SIUE back in Div. 1 nationals after 32 years - The Telegraph - thetelegraph.com<!-- Bot generated title --> |access-date=2014-11-20 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129094203/http://www.thetelegraph.com/news/collegesports-home_top-localsports-sports/50715456/Previous-owners-return |archive-date=2014-11-29 |url-status=dead|df= }}</ref>\n\nIt was frigid on the shoreline of Lake Michigan as the Cougars faced #17 Northwestern on a Thursday afternoon.  Dal Santo found himself in his first game action since the preseason when Kobernus was injured before the game began. In one more battle where two stalwart defenses repeatedly turned away determined offenses, the Wildcats took more shots, 16\u20139, but SIUE trailed only 7\u20138 in shots on goal, with both keepers making several solid saves. Following a corner kick, there was a wild flurry of action directly in front of the Cougar's goal in the 61st minute\u2014 with multiple Wildcats taking shots and several Cougars trying to clear the ball\u2014 lasting a good 10\u201315 seconds before  the ball went over the end line for a goal kick. In the 81st minute, Hackett drove into the left side of the Northwestern box; the Wildcats blocked his shot and tried to clear; Scheipeter located the loose ball and booted his first goal as a Cougar from five yards out to give SIUE the lead. Over the last nine minutes, Northwestern pushed hard, even bringing their All-Big 10 keeper to midfield, but the Cougars' defense held firm for the victory and the right to return to California for a rematch with #18 California in the second round of the tournament.\n<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nusports.com/sports/m-soccer/recaps/112014aaa.html |title=Wildcats Fall 1-0 To SIUE In NCAA Tournament - NUSPORTS.COM - The Northwestern Official Athletic Site<!-- Bot generated title --> |access-date=2014-11-21 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129042246/http://www.nusports.com/sports/m-soccer/recaps/112014aaa.html |archive-date=2014-11-29 |url-status=dead|df= }}</ref>\n\nIn the return trip to California, SIUE took three of the first four and the last three shots in the game, but Cal, the NCAA's top-scoring team, outshot them for the game, 18\u201311.  After a scoreless first half, the Cougars nearly took the lead in the 63rd minute, but Polster's shot banged off the post. In the 71st minute, Dal Santo deflected a shot for a save, but Sekine fired the rebound into the goal to give the Golden Bears a 1\u20130 lead that held up for the victory, sending Cal into the round of 16 and ended the Cougars' season.<ref>[http://www.calbears.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=30100&ATCLID=209779475 Cal advances, knocks off SIUE 1-0 - California Golden Bears - University of California Official Athletic Site<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nWhen the ''2014 NSCAA/Continental Tire NCAA Division I Men's All-Region'' teams were announced on December 10, '''Christian Volesky''' and '''Mat Polster''' were both named to the West Region First Team.<ref>[http://www.nscaa.com/news/2014/12/2014-nscaa-continental-tire-ncaa-division-i-men-s-all-west-region 2014 NSCAA/Continental Tire NCAA Division I Men's All-West Region<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nOn December 11, '''Christian Volesky''' and '''Mat Polster''' were among the 55 college Division I players invited to the 2015 adidas [[MLS Combine|MLS Player Combine]] to showcase their talents to the coaching staffs of all 20 [[Major League Soccer]] clubs.<ref>[http://www.mlssoccer.com/superdraft/2015/news/article/2014/12/11/mls-announces-55-players-invited-2015-adidas-mls-player-combine Major League Soccer announces 55 players invited to 2015 adidas MLS Player Combine | MLSsoccer.com<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n'''Mat Polster''' was named to the 2014 NSCAA Men's University Division ''Scholar All-America First Team'' on December 18.<ref>[http://www.nscaa.com/awards/2014-mens-scholar-all-america-teams--university- 2014 Mens Scholar All-America Teams (University)<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nIn Top Drawer Soccer's (TDS) preseason list of the top 100 college soccer players in the nation, '''Christian Volesky''' was ranked #41, and '''Matt Polster''' was ranked #81.<ref>[http://www.topdrawersoccer.com/college/upperclassmentop100/index.jsp College Soccer Player Rankings - National<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> In the TDS MVC Postseason Top 20, '''Christian Volesky''' was ranked #1, '''Matt Polster''' #2, '''Andrew Kendall-Moullin''' #3, '''Justin Bilyeu''' #6, '''Austin Ledbetter''' #9, '''Garet Christianson''' #10, and '''Paul Scheipeter''' #15.<ref name=autogenerated1 />\n\nAt the 2015 adidas MLS Player Combine, both '''Christian Volesky''' and '''Matt Polster''' had standout performances, with '''Volesky''' being named the ''Tom Fitzgerald MLS Combine Most Valuable Player''.\n\nOn January 15, 2016, MLS held its [[2015 MLS SuperDraft|SuperDraft]]. '''[[Matt Polster]]''' was selected by the [[Chicago Fire Soccer Club|Chicago Fire]] as the 7th overall player taken. '''[[Christian Volesky]]''' was drafted by the [[Portland Timbers]] as the 11th pick in the second round and the 32nd pick overall.<ref>[https://www.si.com/planet-futbol/2015/01/14/2015-mls-superdraft-live-tracker 2015 MLS SuperDraft: As It Happened - Planet Futbol - SI.com<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n==Coaches==\n\nScott Donnelly was named as the Cougars' new head coach on  December 6, 2013 following [[Kevin Kalish]]'s unexpected resignation. Donnelly, former head coach at [[NCAA Division II|Division II]] [[Mars Hill College]] had been the Cougars' associate head coach for the previous two seasons after coming to SIUE from the same position at [[Northern Illinois University|Northern Illinois]]. Assistants are \nfirst year coaches David Korn and  Scott Gyllenborg, seventh year goalkeepers coach Brian Jones, and first year director of operations Billy Berger.\n\nOn August 10, it was announced that coach Scott Donnelly had suddenly and unexpectedly resigned after being recruited to be the new Technical Advisor for the Northeast region with the [[United States Soccer Federation]] (U.S. Soccer). Assistants Korn and Jones were named as co-head coaches for the season due to begin play in earnest on August 29.<ref>[http://www.siuecougars.com/sports/m-soccer/2014-15/releases/20140810w63dxb Donnelly Moves to U.S. Soccer - SIUE<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n==Roster==\n''Source:'' <ref name=\"roster\"/>\n\n<small>Buff background indicates returning players from 2013. Pink background indicates players [[Redshirt (college sports)|\"redshirted\"]] in 2013.\n</small>\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"font-size:95%;\"\n|-\n! #\n! Name\n! Position\n! Height\n! Weight\n! Year\n! Hometown\n! High School\n! Transfer from\n|- style=\" background-color:#F0DC82\"\n| 1\n| Kent Kobernus\n| Goalkeeper\n| 6'\n| 170\n| Senior\n| [[Millstadt, Illinois|Millstadt]], Illinois\n| [[Belleville High School-East|Belleville West]]\n| [[University of Wisconsin-Madison|Wisconsin]]\n|- style=\" background-color:#F0DC82\"\n| 2\n| Andrew Kendall-Moullin\n| Defender\n| 6'\n| 165\n| Sophomore\n| [[Atlanta]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]]<br>[[Faribault, Minnesota]]\n| [[Shattuck-Saint Mary's]]\n|\n|- style=\" background-color:#F0DC82\"\n| 3\n| [[Justin Bilyeu]]\n| Defender\n| 6' 2\"\n| 175\n| Junior\n| [[St. Louis]], [[Missouri]] \n| [[Christian Brothers College High School|CBC]]\n|\n|- style=\" background-color:#F0DC82\"\n| 4\n| [[Matt Polster]]\n| Defender\n| 6\"\n| 170\n| Senior\n| [[Las Vegas, Nevada|Las Vegas]], [[Nevada]] \n| [[Palo Verde High School|Palo Verde]]\n|\n|- style=\" background-color:#F0DC82\"\n| 5\n| Sean Baumann\n| Defender\n| 5'10\"\n| 160\n| Senior\n| [[Makanda, Illinois|Makanda]], [[Illinois]]  \n| [[Carbondale Community High School|Carbondale]]\n| [[Mercer University|Mercer]]\n|- style=\" background-color:#F0DC82\"\n| 6\n| Austin Ledbetter\n| Defender\n| 5'11\"\n| 160\n| Sophomore\n| [[St. Charles, Missouri|St. Charles]], Missouri \n| CBC\n|\n|- style=\" background-color:#F0DC82\"\n| 7\n| Lewis Ellis\n| Forward\n| 5'10\"\n| 175\n| Senior\n| Cambridge, [[Wales]], [[United Kingdom|UK]] \n| [[Millfield|Millfield School]]\n| [[University of Memphis|Memphis]] \n|- style=\" background-color:#F0DC82\"\n| 9\n| Jabari Danzy\n| Midfielder\n| 5' 8\"\n| 160\n| R-Junior\n| [[Park Forest, Illinois|Park Fores